I’d suggest trying to freeform your arrangements in real time. Put everything on an endless loop, hit record and mute parts in real time to build each different section. If you do t have enough diversity in parts when doing that, it means you need to add more tracks to your loop.

Don’t get hung up on the style you are going for, just focus on getting to some kind of end result, you can adjust the styling of it later.

>>114464997
desu you really have to know how to play the drums to program drums that sound real.

But If you just want less robotic sounding, it’s all about syncopation. Syncopation makes the rhythm. You can have the most robotic on-the-grid kick, snare and hats, but when you add another perc sound that accents an off beat in one of the measures, it fixes it and sounds human. The breakbeat sample on top works because it has syncopation in the pattern.

And to preemptively clarify what I mean by accenting the off beats. It’s the extra kick drum hits just before the end of the phrase. It’s the extra snare hit before or after the 2s and 4s. It’s the Tom hit when every other perc is on a rest.

Good tune btw

My take on the matter:
I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing.

Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

One piece of easy, cheap-as-free advice is to envision what a physical setup would be and think about how to recreate digitally. So, for example, if you had a plex turned to 11 you'd stick a sm57 in the sweet spot and a 121 in the middle maybe. Well, that would mean taking two copies of the same guitar wav with the same amp and cab sims and treating them different in terms of eq. lol this is the hard way to make a melody.

some people start here. or some people figure out major/minor scales modes etc and try to use those to make melodies.. but again it's too many notes in my opinion to easily make a good melody.

Simplify it down to the pentatonic scale OR a six note scale. By six note scale, I mean like the major scale with the fourth removed, or a minor scale without the 6th.
It helps if you can improvise around these scales too.
Most melodies are really simple and only use these notes.
Going up and down scales is a good way to make amateur sounding melodies. Leave some notes out, the ones that don't sound that good, just play the notes that sound good. Easy.

Should I make a youtube video about this with a basedface caption called the SECRET METHOD to melody making the pros don't want you to know?

>>114491706
its a bit free form and it depends on what you want to make
Like if I want to make a bell then I might start with filter envelopes first to get the base of sound down and then get to messing around with EQ/distortion for harmonics and adding reverb or delay at the end to make it sound dreamy and complete
If i want something like a reese bass then I might start with the wave shaping first and then modulating different filters after
Once you understand the basics and you've listened to enough music you get an ear for hearing what and how sounds are made up of, Most sounds you'll hear are made with some type of gimmick or technique, they're usually not some super complex engineering other than a few niche EDM genres like hardstyle kicks or neurobass leads/basses

posts.com: What's your prod process? Coming from playing live instruments, DAWs have me at a loss for where to begin a song.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114512344
I learned to avoid the pressure of creating and finishing a song. I simply split up the whole process into different sessions:
>sound design session
I sit down and play around with synths, samples and plugins and create sounds that I like. Sometimes this turns into a 4 bar or 8 bar loop I save.
>sample session
I have an Excel list of tracks I listened to that I wanted to sample. So I sit down and just do that. Sometimes I look around on specific blogs posting really old albums and if I like something I sample it. A little bit processing, maybe a loop, chopping up some drum breaks... and save it.
>producing session
This is when I sit down and turn the stuff I created in the other sessions into songs. Taking a loop from the sound design or sample session and building around it. Sometimes I open up other projects and continue working on them.
>mixing/mastering session
No need to explain much. Finished songs get mixed or mastered for uploads.

You are now focused on the process and not on the goal. Sometimes I feel creative and sometimes not, but in both cases I have a session I can do. Of course there is also a situation where I switch from a sample or sound design session to a producing session because I have an idea.

I mostly know about Middle Eastern Arabic music so I'll try to tell you more about that. What music helped you determine that you enjoy it? I can better tailor my response to your tastes if you tell me more about what you like (genres, moods, etc). I'll stick to classics for now though. My picks will of course be biased to my tastes (long, moody, and slow songs) and there is a lot more variety in Arabic music than I will represent (especially as you listen to more music and your ears get acclimated to the foreign music). Since you're on /mu/ I'll assume you have no problem with longer songs.
If you want the classics you should probably listen to music from what's considered the "Golden Age" of Arabic music. Unfortunately given how long ago that was, this could be a problem if you care about audio quality and mixing. The most popular genre of the time was "Tarab" but I'll give you some more variety. The biggest artists from this time are:
Umm Kulthum

when you modulate, write the tonic of the new key. use a capital letter if it's major, or lowercase if it's minor. then write the chords relative to the new key. it's fine if the chords you write aren't in the scale, just use the root note and chord type to determine the symbol to write. for your progression, that would look like:
bb: iiiØ / II / vi
g#: (your chords here)
if the root note of your chord isn't in the scale at all, just use the b (flat) symbol in front of the roman numeral you want to write to denote the right chord. (if you wanted to play a Bmaj7 chord in Bbm, you could write "bII" to denote this)

To me they were simply the last great hope of UK rock. The first album rocks like a motherfucker while still having hooks on hooks and continues the great lineage of Kinks - Jam - Blur of snarky realist lyrics. Btw I like AM, it's overplayed, teen girls masturbated to it ten years ago, idgaf. it's the last rock record that has anything to say about rock and roll and still have cultural relevance and swag too.

>>114518937
>expecting a reasonable discussion of the music of a transexual artist
>on /mu/

anyway her sound design seemed incredible to me but unfortunately she died so fucking quick it feels like we didn't even get enough to tell what we're missing out on. with only two live-action music videos plus a few visualisers it's impossible to say what she would have done next on the audiovisual front, which seemed to be one of her biggest draws. even joy division got 2 albums + a bunch pf non-album singles to establish their trajectory before ian died so e.g. we can see the progression from warsaw to atmosphere. sophie died just a little too soon to have even that artistic impact, though of course the emotional impact of her death on the lgbt community is probably bigger proportionally for how much smaller a population it is. overall, it seems her legacy will be closer to jeff buckley than a nick drake or an ian curtis, highly regarded but too short-lived and elusive to truly make it into the top-tier late greats. i'm more of a guitar music fan myself than a clubber so i can't offer much judgement on her music but i could tell the control she exerted over the sound design was very impressive.

>>114519678
Completely disagree. To me, Aladdin Sane is his most fully realized glam album, even more than Ziggy Stardust. I think the songs on Ziggy Stardust are better, and that it's a better album overall, but it feels like Ziggy Stardust is a concept album about Ziggy Stardust, while Aladdin Sane is meatier, heavier, sometimes weirder, and more immediate songs BY Ziggy Stardust. In a way it sounds more proto-punk. My favorite songs on it are Cracked Actor and Time - Cracked Actor is a great, sexual hard rock song that's edgier than anything sexually driven hard rock bands like Aerosmith were doing at the time. Time is a weirder, more off-kilter song than anything on Ziggy Stardust (or Diamond Dogs, for that matter, though I love the song Big Brother).

I think Aladdin Sane is a really solid album, and while I would give Ziggy Stardust a slight edge, the only album from that period I'd really say is objectively superior to it is Hunky Dory.

>>114496636
These are their albums worth checking out

>Killing Technology
Proggy thrash metal
>Dimension Hatross
Thrashy prog metal, less emphasis on the thrash. Probably their proggiest album.
>Nothingface
Progressive metal with a pretty unique post-punk edge, not so much thrash metal
>The Outer Limits
Pretty solid prog metal with a clear early 90s alternative rock sound. Jack Luminous is their best song.
>The Wake
Surprisingly great return to form to their Dimension Hatross sound after 25 years of mediocrity

Their first two albums aren't prog.
Angel Rat's a weird alternative rock/metal album, some people like it but it's not prog.
Negatron is their obligatory 1990s 80s-thrash-metal-band-gone-butt-metal album but with Voivod's signature angular dissonant riffing style.
Phobos is Negatron but more spaced out and proggy, might be worth listening to if you don't mind 90s butt metal.

Literally everything Voivod's put out in the 2000s and early 2010s has been unremarkable until The Wake.

Opiates (Heroin): A death trip. You'll lose touch with all your human feelings when you've gone too far. The sad and unspoken truth about overdoses is, most of them happen to people who are ready to welcome death.
Marijuana: Smoke up. No harm done. Take a break now and then when you stop getting high - usually a month will do it.
Ecstasy (I think you people call it "Molly" - MDMA in any case): Loses the desired effect after heavy use for about a year. I have always been a bit of a weird person. I was an especially weird kid. I was diagnosed with Asperger’s syndrome at age 12. I used to exhibit a lot of classic signs of autism, and it caused me to struggle a lot with my social interactions. Growing up was tough for me up until about age 15. Eventually I learned to overcome a lot of the things that were keeping me back, I became much more adept at social interaction, I was able to channel my hyperfixations into productive avenues, I stopped stimming, I wouldn’t make weird or strange observations or comments, I overcame a lot of my sensory aversions involving food, I became more physically active, and less afraid of water etc etc. I feel as though I’ve gotten to a point where I can fully function as a person. People do realise I’m weird and sometimes as they grow closer to me, do ask me if I’m slightly autistic, but it’s nothing too major, and it doesn’t hold me back or significantly impact my social life.

The one major autistic trait that hasn’t left me is an extremely obsessive personality. Throughout my life I have jumped head first from one niche obsession to another, becoming totally captivated by a subject, learning about it at an incredibly fast rate, often accumulating large collections (Pokémon cards, hot wheels, etc) and then eventually losing interest and moving on to the next. I’ve been into hip hop since 2016 but discovering JPEGMAFIA and death grips in a bigger way opened my mind to experimental music, and in mid April of 2022, I was introduced to Syro by Aphex Twin. Words will never, ever, be able to describe how that was for me.

My roommates are pretty cool people, and we have a room in the house dedicated to listening to music, with a very high quality surround sound system. We have blocked out all the light in the room so we can listen to full albums in the pitch black, which is really cool. We went as far as to put tape over the lights from all the electronic devices, so it really is pitch black. I had never experienced mild synthesesia and closed eye colour/shape visuals from music before, but it happens often now.

I have since gotten extremely into IDM in general, drill and bass, acid house, ambient techno, breakcore, gabber, house, juke, big beat, progressive house, hardgroove, acid breaks, etc

Squarepusher, venetian snares, boards of Canada, DJ Camgirl, Golden Boy, I really love bogdan raczynski, soft blade, the field, the prodigy, machine girl, death’s dynamic shroud, bye2, fatboy slim, the chemical brothers, etc etc, but above all, aphex twin.

Unfortunately, however, since discovering aphex twin, I feel like my autism has come back.

We had a small party at my place recently, my roommate and I smoked weed right before everyone arrived, and it was a little bit intense. I really didn’t feel like socialising so I asked my friend if we could duck out to the listening room, and we just geeked out and listened to aphex twin for 2 hours. We were basically hosting and we just completely disappeared. The folks at the party straight up left and we didn’t even know, I felt really bad the day after. This was the day before I made my last post on r/aphextwin about how Richard D James is a genius.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114517926

I have always constantly had music in my head, I also have an ADHD diagnosis, but since discovering aphex I have started stimming again, often to the beat of some batshit insane aphex twin track. I tap my fingers on objects with good acoustics, I click my fingers, I tap my feet, I play beats in my mouth and music in my head, using my teeth as drums and bass, I can get snare sounds, I can get kick drums, I can even do rushing sounds by moving saliva through my mouth a certain way. I have literally started eroding the enamel on my teeth and I’ve been told to stop by multiple dentists, but I can’t.

I’m always inadvertently working Aphex twin into totally unrelated conversations. It makes sense in my head, every discussion seems to logically progress into aphex twin in some way or another, and it is genuine, but I’ve been told multiple times that it seems like I’m just trying to shoehorn him into every discussion.

I constantly recommend aphex twin when it’s not appropriate. The other day someone told me that they like nirvana, pantera, and tool, and I told him to listen to cock/ver10. I saw him at work yesterday and when I asked him if he liked the track he almost yelped?? He hasn’t spoken to me since.

I’ve started making weird niche aphex twin jokes that people don’t understand. I somehow don’t really care that they don’t get it, it’s not even their fault, but opportunities present themselves so often it’s just low hanging fruit. It’s also forbidden fruit in a way.. This is something I used to do and had overcome as I grew up, and it’s really frustrating and scary to literally feel myself revert socially in this respect. Sometimes they’re in really poor taste too. I was talking to a co worker who’s child has cancer, and before I could even think about what I was doing, I called her kid a “weakling child”.
